        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="Kali106-kilavi">itu tattam iṉan tattam pulattup pirippāṉ pukkavar ēṟu koṇṭavāṟu kaṇṭu āycciyar taṅkātaṉ mikutiyāṟ ṟaṅ kātalaraik kaipiṇaintu kuravaiyāṭit teṉṉaṉ vāḻkeṉak kāṉam pāṭiyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en"></p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="Kali106">
                <l>kaḻuvoṭu cuṭupaṭai curukkiya tōṟkaṇ </l>
                <l>ṇimiḻicai maṇṭai yuṟiyoṭu tūkki</l>
                <l>yoḻukiya koṉṟait tīṅkuḻaṉ muraṟciyar </l>
                <l>vaḻūuccoṟ kōvalar tatta miṉanirai </l>
                <l>poḻutoṭu tōṉṟiya kārnaṉai viyaṉpulattar; </l>
                <l rend="space">avvaḻi, </l>
                <l>nīṟe ṭuppavai nilañcā ṭupavai </l>
                <l>māṟēṟṟuc cilaippavai maṇṭippāy pavaiyāyt </l>
                <l>tuḷaṅkimi ṉallēṟ ṟiṉampala kaḷampuku </l>
                <l>maḷḷar vaṉappot taṉa; </l>
                <l rend="space">tākkupu tammuṭ peyarttoṟṟi yevvāyum </l>
                <l>vaivāy maruppiṉāṉ māṟātu kuttaliṉ </l>
                <l>meyvār kurutiya vēṟellām peykālaik </l>
                <l>koṇṭa ṉiraiyot taṉa; </l>
                <l rend="space">avvēṟṟai,</l>
                <l>pirivukoṇ ṭiṭaippōkki yiṉattoṭu puṉattēṟṟi </l>
                <l>yirutiṟaṉā nīkkum potuva </l>
                <l>rurukeḻu mānila miyaṟṟuvāṉ </l>
                <l>viritirai nīkkuvāṉ viyaṉkuṟip pottaṉar; </l>
                <l rend="space">avaraik, kaḻala vuḻakki yetirceṉṟu cāṭi </l>
                <l>yaḻalvāy maruppiṉāṟ kutti yuḻalai </l>
                <l>marattaippōṟ ṟoṭṭaṉa vēṟu; </l>
                <l rend="space">toṭṭatam, puṇvār kurutiyāṟ kaipicaintu meytimirit </l>
                <l>taṅkār potuvar kaṭaluṭ paratava </l>
                <l>rampiyūrn tāṅkūrntā rēṟu; </l>
                <l rend="space">ēṟutaṅ, kōlañcey maruppiṉāṟ ṟōṇṭiya varikkuṭar </l>
                <l>ñālakkoṇ ṭeḻūum paruntiṉ vāyvaḻīi </l>
                <l>yāluṅ kaṭampu maṇimār vilaṅkiṭṭa </l>
                <l>mālaipōṟ ṟūṅkuñ ciṉai; </l>
                <l rend="space">āṅku,</l>
                <l>tampula vēṟu parattara vuyttata </l>
                <l>maṉpuṟu kātalar kaipiṇain tāycciya </l>
                <l>riṉpuṟ ṟayarvar taḻūu; </l>
                <l rend="space">muyaṅkip potivē muyaṅkip potivē </l>
                <l>mulaivēti ṉoṟṟi muyaṅkip potivēṅ </l>
                <l>kolaiyēṟu cāṭiya puṇṇaiyeṅ kēḷē; </l>
                <l rend="space">pallūḻ tayirkaṭaiyat tāaya puḷḷimēṟ </l>
                <l>kollēṟu koṇṭāṉ kuruti mayakkuṟap </l>
                <l>pullalen tōḷiṟ kaṇiyōveṅ kēḷē; </l>
                <l rend="space">āṅkup, </l>
                <l>pōrēṟ ṟaruntalai yañcalu māycciyar </l>
                <l>kārikait tōḷkā muṟutalu mivviraṇṭu </l>
                <l>mōrāṅkuc cēṟa lilavōveṅ kēḷē;</l>
                <l rend="space">kollēṟu koṇṭā ṉivaḷkēḷva ṉeṉṟūrār </l>
                <l>colluñcoṟ kēḷā vaḷaimāṟi yāmvaruñ </l>
                <l>celvameṅ kēḷvaṉ ṟarumōveṅ kēḷē;</l>
                <l rend="space">āṅka, </l>
                <l>aruntalai yēṟṟoṭu kātalarp pēṇic </l>
                <l>curumpimir kāṉanām pāṭiṉam paravutu </l>
                <l>mēṟṟavar pulaṅkeṭat tiṟaikoṇṭu </l>
                <l>māṟṟāraik kaṭakkavem maṟaṅkeḻu kōvē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l corresp="2">Hanging up [their] earthen pots with buzzing sound with pot nets</l>
                <l corresp="1">on skin curtailed by blades burned in wood blocks</l>
                <l corresp="3">those whose sounds [come from] the flowing sweet Koṉṟai flutes,</l>
                <l>the cowherders with faulty words are on the wide fields wet</l>
                <l corresp="4f">from the rainy season that appeared in time with all their herds.</l>
                <l>That way,</l>
                <l>those that raise dust, that trample the ground,</l>
                <l>that rage against enemy bulls, that rush [and] leap</l>
                <l>– many herds of good bulls with swaying humps enter the floor</l>
                <l corresp="6-10">[and] equal warriors in beauty.</l>
                <l>All the bulls that blood flowing from [their] bodies</l>
                <l>because they attack, press in repeatedly among them in every spot</l>
                <l>[and] pierce without retreating with [there] sharp-tipped horns,</l>
                <l corresp="11-14">equal a row of clouds on a rainy morning.</l>
                <l>Those bulls,</l>
                <l>separating them [and] making them go into the middle, raising the field with the herd,</l>
                <l>the herdsmen who put aside the cows in big groups(?)</l>
                <l>are alike in the wide intention of preparing(?) the beautiful dark ground</l>
                <l corresp="15-19">[and] repelling the expanding waves. </l> 
                <l>Those [herdsmen], ravaging them when they come loose, going against [them and] trampling [them],</l>
                <l>piercing [them] with [their] fire-tipped horns</l>
                <l corresp="20-22">the bulls pierced through [them] like through wooden bars.</l>
                <l>Those the pierced [them through],</l>
                <l>[their] hands wiping [and] smearing [their] bodies with the blood overflowing from [their] wounds,</l>
                <l>the herdsmen won’t stay, [but] they mount the bulls</l>
                <l corresp="23-25">like fishermen in the sea mount [their] boats.</l>
                <l>The intestines in lines beautifully carved out by the horns of the bulls,</l>
                <l>slipping out of the beaks of the kites that rise to the world,</l>
                <l>hang in branches like garlands,</l>
                <l corresp="26-29">placed [there] in order to adorn the banyan- and Kadamba trees.</l>
                <l>Thus,</l>
                <l>the cowherdesses, entwining [their] hands with their loving lovers</l>
                <l>who sent out the bulls to spread in their fields,</l>
                <l corresp="30-33">pleasantly engage in embracing. </l>
                <l>We shall embrace [and] cover, we shall embrace [and] cover</l>
                <l>pressing, if the breast burns, we shall embrace [and] cover</l>
                <l corresp="34-36">the wound torn by the murderous bull on our kinsman.</l>
                <l>While we churn curds many turns, embracing our kinsman</l>
                <l>so that the blood on him who took the murderous bull</l>
                <l corresp="37-39">gets mixed up in spots that spread, will [that] by an adornment to our shoulder?</l>
                <l>Thus,</l>
                <l>fearing the head, difficult [to take], of the fighting bull</l> 
                <l>and desiring the beautiful shoulders of the cowherdesses, </l>
                <l corresp="40-43">won’t these two things join like one for our kinsman?</l>
                <l>When, upon hearing the words the villagers say: “the man who took the bull </l>
                <l>is her husband”, we come, exchanging curds,</l>
                <l corresp="44-46">will our husband bring wealth, our kinsman?</l>
                <l>Thus,</l>
                <l>honouring with the bulls with heads difficult [to take] the lovers,</l>
                <l>we will revere ???, being ones who sang the forest buzzing with bees:</l>
                <l>as the region of the foes gets lost, let our valorous king </l>
                <l corresp="47-51">taken tribute [and] overcome [his] enemies.</l>
            </lg>
